Rating: 1
I actually didn't even get the sauce on the chicken as the recipe calls because once the sauce was prepared and I tasted it I couldn't even imagine ruining my chicken like tha. I couldn't taste any spice or sweetness, just very tart, sour, and vinegary. I ended up adding cayenne, honey, brown sugar, and apricot preserves. It cut the tartness but I still wouldn't recommend the recipe even with the additions.

Rating: 4
Meat is something I don't eat every day and not even every week, but when I read this BBQ sauce recipe, I hurried to buy chicken for it - three times (the last 3rd of the sauce stayed in the freezer only one week). I put the chicken on the top rack of a preheated 400-425 degree oven (leave preheat on to keep both elements hot while roasting) on a rack over a foil lined baking sheet for about twenty minutes to quick melt the fat into the meat and quick crisp the skin before twice dipping the pieces in the sauce warming on the stove and then returning them to the oven. When the chicken is almost done, turn off the oven and let it sit in there carmelizing the sauce even further and soaking into the meat until you are excessively salivating. What an exceptional, tangy, thick, gooey, toothsome, smoky, spicy, beautifully colored BBQ sauce with the added bonus of using those dried tart cherries languishing in the pantry after the holidays.

Rating: 3
Very good but not as stellar as I hoped. Next time I will use two more ancho chilie for more heat--not hot enough (or at all) for my taste with just two. Instead of brown sugar I increased molasses to 4 Tble and used 4 Tble aguave nectar (I'm trying to cut down/avoid refined sugar). Like other reviewers I brined chicken in salt water for 30 min first, used fresh cherries and drumsticks. I also added an extra clove of garlic and cooked on a stove top grill. Turned out very good though my cooking time was closer to 30 minutes and I had to have every fan in the house going to avoid smoke alarm!

Rating: 4
This was a fantastic hit for everyone, young and old! It had a little bit of a kick, but not too much at all. I didn't have coriander and clove, so I used cinnamon instead, and it worked beautifully. We couldn't get enough of this sauce!

Rating: 4
This was a lovely recipe. I used chicken drumsticks and they turned out very flavorful. I did sub 1 tbsp ancho chili powder for the actual chilies. I also could not find dried sour cherries, so I subbed dried cranberries. This is definitely a keeper recipe!

